# Local Engineering — SwarmForge VC (VS Code Extension)

Specializes the shared Engineering Rules for this project. Additive only; the
shared article remains in force.

## Tech Stack
- Language: TypeScript.
- Platform: Visual Studio Code extension (standard VS Code Extension API). Must
  also work in Cursor (a VS Code fork) — target the standard API only; nothing
  Cursor-specific.
- Standard scaffold (yo code / generator-code): normal package.json manifest,
  activation events, contributed commands.
- UI tiles render in a VS Code Webview.
- Node.js APIs (child_process, etc.) are available in the extension host for
  shelling out to tmux and git.
- Target OS: macOS and Linux only. Do not write Windows-specific code; the swarm
  substrate depends on tmux.

## Conventions
- Extension-host code and webview code stay clearly separated: different
  execution contexts, communicating only via postMessage. Never share state
  directly.
- The extension host owns all I/O: tmux, `.swarmforge/` files, git. The webview
  is presentation plus forwarded user input.
- Prefer small, testable modules (see shared Design And Testability — the
  webview and VS Code API surface are the unsuitable boundary).
- Command IDs namespaced under `swarmforge.` (swarmforge.run, swarmforge.stop,
  swarmforge.setTarget, swarmforge.initTarget).

## Architecture Rules
1. Two layers: tile-as-view, tmux-as-substrate. Tiles are TypeScript/webview
   VIEWS; tmux is the process SUBSTRATE running the agents. These are layers,
   not alternatives. Do NOT spawn agent processes directly from TypeScript to
   bypass tmux — if a task starts to feel like rebuilding process orchestration,
   stop: that is the signal the line was crossed.
2. Swarm machinery relationship. The swarm machinery under `swarmforge/` in this
   repo is a **maintained fork** of unclebob/swarm-forge, not an unmodified
   dependency. Local modifications are deliberate and tracked; upstream changes
   enter only through the drift-watch review (`upstream-watch.json`,
   `docs/upstream-deviations.md`), never by automatic fetch. The bootstrap
   wrapper must fetch helper scripts from a pinned by-SHA tarball, not a
   floating branch head.
3. Webview storage restriction. No localStorage, sessionStorage, or any browser
   storage in the webview. UI state lives in memory or persists via the
   extension host (workspace state / files).
4. Secrets. Tokens and keys (e.g. a GitHub token for opening PRs) live in the
   extension host environment only. Never written into the target working
   directory or any commit.
5. Two phone-viewable surfaces, one boundary — pick correctly at spec time.
   TWO web surfaces are phone-viewable and are NOT interchangeable: (a) the
   STATIC backlog-dashboard PWA (`pwa/index.html` -> `pwa/app.js`), a pure
   renderer fetching `./backlog.json` — a git-SHA-reproducible PROJECTION
   with NO bridge/host connectivity, NO auth, NO write path; and (b) the LIVE
   holistic UI (`extension/src/bridge/holisticUiHtml.ts`, served by
   `bridge/bridgeServer.ts`) with token auth, live endpoints, and control
   actions. Only git-SHA-derivable data may ride the static PWA; route any
   live/machine-local/write-path need to the LIVE holistic UI instead —
   confirm which surface a request means before speccing. (Recurred 3x in
   2026-07-10: BL-252 suite-duration trend, BL-265 gate-answer view, BL-257
   slices 3-4 changed-since-visit + live trends.) See
   **local-engineering-detailed.prompt** for the fuller narrative.
6. Epics have icons representing musical forms, on TWO distinct surfaces
   with two distinct realisations — never one implementation assumed to
   cover both: the PWA/fleet-console/bot-avatar surfaces carry the owned
   orchestra FORM marks (Symphony/Concerto/Suite/Fugue/Overture —
   `docs/branding/icon-system.md` §4d); Telegram topic icons stand in with
   the closest stock PERFORMANCE sticker instead, since
   `getForumTopicIconStickers` offers no notation/instrument glyphs. See
   **local-engineering-detailed.prompt** for the BL-449 platform-wall
   rationale.

## Diagrams (this project)
Per the shared Diagrams rule, the diagrams this project maintains are:
1. **Architecture diagram** — the two-layer system: extension host,
   webview(s), the tmux substrate, `.swarmforge/` state, handoffd and the
   queue helpers, and the boundaries between them (what talks to what, and
   over which channel: postMessage, files, tmux socket, git).
2. **Swarm workflow flow diagram** — the CURRENT parcel flow: intake at the
   backlog root, specifier speccing to paused/, coordinator promotion and
   assignment, the specifier→coder→cleaner→architect→hardender→documenter→QA
   chain, QA approval, merge-up broadcast to worktree roles, and coordinator
   integration on `main` (close ticket, promote next). When the pipeline
   topology or backlog flow changes, this diagram changes in the same
   parcel.
Both live under `docs/diagrams/` as Mermaid sources.

## Key Integration Surface
Prove these against a real swarm install, in order, before UI polish:
1. Launch a swarm against a target path by shelling to ./swarm.
2. Discover the tmux socket (.swarmforge/tmux-socket) and enumerate
   sessions/windows/panes.
3. Tail one pane's output into a webview tile, live.
4. Send keystrokes INTO a pane (fiddliest cross-platform piece — tackle early).
5. Read .swarmforge/ state to know which stage holds the work.
6. Open a PR from the dev branch into the target's main via git + GitHub CLI/API.

If any of these cannot be done from outside the swarm machinery, note it clearly
as a candidate change to the fork (via the normal backlog), rather than working
around it ad hoc.
